Summary
The Definition (&lt;dfn&gt;)&nbsp;HTML element represents the defining instance of a term.
HTML5 Usage Notes:
 The &lt;dfn&gt; element marks the term being defined; the definition of the term should be given by the surrounding &lt;p&gt;
, &lt;section&gt;
 or definition list group (usually a &lt;dt&gt;
, &lt;dd&gt;
 pair). The exact value of the term being defined is determined by the following rules:  If the &lt;dfn&gt; element has a title attribute, then the term is the value of that attribute. Else, if it contains only an &lt;abbr&gt;
 element with a 

title
 attribute, then the term is the value of that attribute. Otherwise, the text content of the &lt;dfn&gt; element is the term being defined.  


Attributes
Like all HTML&nbsp;elements, this element provides the global attributes. It defines no other attributes. In HTML5, the title attribute has special meaning, as noted above.
Examples
The following examples are valid in HTML5.

          &lt;!-- Define &quot;The Internet&quot; --&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;dfn id=&quot;def-internet&quot;&gt;The Internet&lt;/dfn&gt; is a global system of interconnected networks that use the Internet Protocol Suite (TCP/IP) to serve billions of users worldwide.&lt;/p&gt;

Later in the same document:

          &lt;dl&gt;
  &lt;!-- Define &quot;World-Wide Web&quot; and reference definition for &quot;the Internet&quot; --&gt;
  &lt;dt&gt;
    &lt;dfn&gt;
      &lt;abbr title=&quot;World-Wide Web&quot;&gt;WWW&lt;/abbr&gt;
    &lt;/dfn&gt;
  &lt;/dt&gt;
  &lt;dd&gt;The World-Wide Web (WWW) is a system of interlinked hypertext documents accessed on &lt;a href=&quot;#def-internet&quot;&gt;the Internet&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/dd&gt;
&lt;/dl&gt;

DOM interface
This element implements the HTMLElement interface.
See also
 Elements related to definition lists:&nbsp;&lt;dl&gt;
, &lt;dt&gt;
, &lt;dd&gt;
