Summary
In a web form, the HTML optgroup element (&lt;optgroup&gt;) creates a grouping of options within a &lt;select&gt;
 element.
Usage context
   Permitted content Zero or more &lt;option&gt;
 elements.   Tag omission The start tag is mandatory. The end tag is optional if this element is immediately followed by&nbsp; another &lt;optgroup&gt; element, or if the parent element has no more content.   Permitted parent elements  A &lt;select&gt;
 element.    Normative document HTML 5, Section 4.10.11; HTML 4.0.1, Section 17.6  

Note:&nbsp;Optgroup elements may not be nested.

Attributes
Like all other HTML&nbsp;elements, this element has the global attributes.


disabled If this Boolean attribute is set, none of the items in this option group is selectable. Often browsers grey out such control and it won't received any browsing events, like mouse clicks or focus-related ones. 

label The name of the group of options, which the browser can use when labeling the options in the user interface. This attribute is mandatory if this element is used.

Example

          &lt;select&gt;
  &lt;optgroup label=&quot;Group 1&quot;&gt;
    &lt;option&gt;Option 1.1&lt;/option&gt;
  &lt;/optgroup&gt; 
  &lt;optgroup label=&quot;Group 2&quot;&gt;
    &lt;option&gt;Option 2.1&lt;/option&gt;
    &lt;option&gt;Option 2.2&lt;/option&gt;
  &lt;/optgroup&gt;
  &lt;optgroup label=&quot;Group 3&quot; disabled&gt;
    &lt;option&gt;Option 3.1&lt;/option&gt;
    &lt;option&gt;Option 3.2&lt;/option&gt;
    &lt;option&gt;Option 3.3&lt;/option&gt;
  &lt;/optgroup&gt;
&lt;/select&gt;

&lt;form&gt;  
Option 1.1

Option 2.1
Option 2.2

Option 3.1
Option 3.2
Option 3.3
  &lt;/form&gt;
